explanation:
For verifying MISRA rule about safe use of <string.h> functions you must examine not only the target function but any called code (and the types/macros that determine object sizes and layouts) that could perform string/memory operations on pointer parameters used here. Reasons for each symbol:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Direct callee that returns return_code and populates the token; its implementation must be inspected for any use of memcpy/memmove/memset/strcpy/strncpy/strlen/etc on inputs or on the token that could access out-of-bounds memory.

- OS_CondVarSignal_Impl: Direct callee executed when OS_ObjectIdGetById succeeds; may manipulate the token or related structures and could call string functions — must be checked.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: These are transitive callees of OS_ObjectIdGetById (per the static call graph). Any of them may perform memory or string operations while converting/validating IDs/tokens or indexing object tables; their implementations are required to evaluate potential out-of-bounds accesses.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Transitive callee of OS_CondVarSignal_Impl. It converts a token to an index/reference into internal tables; its code may perform pointer arithmetic or memory copies that need review.

- OS_object_token_t, osal_id_t, int32: Type definitions are needed to know the sizes, layout and pointer semantics of the token and id parameters so you can determine whether any string/memory operation in the callees could exceed object bounds.

- OS_SUCCESS, OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: Macros/enum values used as parameters and return checks; required to understand control flow (when the_IMPL is invoked) and to trace which code paths are relevant to the analysis.

- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These unit-test stub APIs appear in the static call graph for this function (test/instrumentation builds may route calls through them). If the build under analysis uses these stubs, their implementations could substitute behavior that includes string/memory operations; include them to be certain no string.h functions are invoked by test harness code in the call chain.

In short: inspect the implementations of these listed functions and review the listed types/macros to determine whether any use of standard string functions occurs and, if so, whether those calls can access beyond the bounds of the referenced objects.
